I am not sure if I understand cācapī. FN. 5 here says, probably with reference to (pi): "Superfluous." This probably means that the ()s here mean: deleted by the editor. The [general] Ed. adds: "Or perhaps APICA is meant."
--><!--
BD: I'm not sure what the "superfluous" is meant to apply to, but I think it concerns the whole cācapī thing, which the editor suggests may have been meant for api ca. I think both are wrong, and we have the queen's name here. (I have no idea if the name of this guy's queen is attested anywhere - I may be completely wrong.) Both the c-s in cācapī could well be v-s (actually I think v is more likely than c), and the p could be ṣ, though p is more likely. We may or may not have ca between mama and the beginning of c. Neither combination yields a very convincing name, but perhaps mama+ca+āvuṣī is the least implausible.
-->bhaṭṭ<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>rikāyāś ca d<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice><surplus>ṁ</surplus>mpa<surplus>ṁ</surplus>tyasyāsmākam anugrahārttha<choice><sic>M</sic><corr>ṁ</corr></choice> parāśara-sa<lb
